"The Great Wall of China and the famous\u00a0\nterracotta army vividly symbolize the power\u00a0\u00a0 of ancient China\u2014to the point that they have\u00a0\neven been featured in movies . In The Mummy:\u00a0\u00a0 Tomb of the Dragon Emperor , a 2008 release\u00a0\nthat did no honor to the 1999 classic,\u00a0\u00a0 the army even came back to life .\nThe historical creator of the\u00a0\u00a0 real terracotta army, the first\u00a0\nemperor of China, Qin Shi Huang,\u00a0\u00a0 probably conscripted some 700,000 workers to\u00a0\ncreate his massive mausoleum. It covers an area\u00a0\u00a0 of about 56 square kilometers and includes the\u00a0\nterracotta army, with its 8,000 clay soldiers,\u00a0\u00a0 130 chariots, and nearly 800 horses. These\u00a0\nfigures represent China's army at the time,\u00a0\u00a0 an army more powerful than China had ever had.\u00a0\nThis army allowed Qin Shi Huang, the king of Qin,\u00a0\u00a0 to unite the warring states of China and unify\u00a0\nthem under his rule as the first emperor.\u00a0 Before Qin Shi Huang unified China, the region\u00a0\nconsisted of seven states that struggled for\u00a0\u00a0 power. This era, known as the warring states\u00a0\nperiod, is the subject of many Chinese myths,\u00a0\u00a0 legends, and even modern movies. For example, in\u00a0\nthe film genre wuxia history and legend blur. A\u00a0\u00a0 famous example is the 2002 film Hero, starring\u00a0\nJet Li. Mythological and historical elements\u00a0\u00a0 are linked not only in popular media but also in\u00a0\nhow the Chinese perceive their history. To get a\u00a0\u00a0 clear view of China's early history, we need to\u00a0\nuntangle the history from the myth. To do that,\u00a0\u00a0 we will jump back even further, and take a\u00a0\nlook at how the sparsely populated China of\u00a0\u00a0 the Stone Age developed into a complex network of\u00a0\nwarring states and, eventually, a mighty empire.\u00a0 Chapter 1: The First Traces of War\nAbout 12,000 years ago, the ice from\u00a0\u00a0 the last Ice Age melted. The hunter-gatherers\u00a0\nthat had lived in East Asia for more than 100,000\u00a0\u00a0 years began to settle near rivers and swamps,\u00a0\nespecially in the south of present-day China\u00a0\u00a0 and along the Yangtze and Yellow Rivers. Over the\u00a0\nfollowing millennia, they developed a sedentary\u00a0\u00a0 way of life based on agriculture. People lived\u00a0\ntogether in clans; cultivated millet, cabbage,\u00a0\u00a0 and hemp; and raised pigs, dogs, and chickens.\u00a0\nAs usually happens when permanent settlements\u00a0\u00a0 are established, the increasing contact between\u00a0\ntribes and cultures led to conflicts and therefore\u00a0\u00a0 the need for protection. For this reason,\u00a0\npeople soon built low stone walls or ditches\u00a0\u00a0 around their settlements. At first, these had\u00a0\na double function: they prevented livestock\u00a0\u00a0 from wandering off, and they were an obstacle for\u00a0\nraiders. Somewhat later, in the Middle Stone Age,\u00a0\u00a0 which lasted from about 7,000 to 5,000 BC in\u00a0\nChina, the first earthen ramparts, combined\u00a0\u00a0 with ditches, emerged in the Yangtze River basin.\u00a0\nThey primarily served a military function, making\u00a0\u00a0 them the first indisputable traces of violent\u00a0\nconflict between groups in China. According\u00a0\u00a0 to the historian Kauschik Roy, these initial\u00a0\nconflicts mainly involved small-scale fighting\u00a0\u00a0 between villages, cattle raids, and feuds.\nThe fortified settlements turned into cities\u00a0\u00a0 throughout the next millennia, and their small\u00a0\nearthen walls became impressive fortifications.\u00a0\u00a0 One of the numerous Neolithic cultures found\u00a0\nin China , the Liangzhu culture, was located\u00a0\u00a0 in the lower reaches of the Yangtze River around\u00a0\n3,300\u20132,300 BC and is known to have had cities of\u00a0\u00a0 up to 30,000 people. The Longshan culture also\u00a0\nhad large cities and, in the 3rd millennium BC,\u00a0\u00a0 massive ramparts of rammed earth that were up\u00a0\nto 25m wide. This construction technique was\u00a0\u00a0 still used in China about four millennia later\u00a0\nwhen the Ming built their capitals in Nanjing\u00a0\u00a0 and Beijing. The sheer size of these cities and\u00a0\nfortifications makes clear that the Liangzhu and\u00a0\u00a0 Longshan cultures were complex communities that\u00a0\nhad mastered many cultural skills. These included,\u00a0\u00a0 for example, the cultivation of rice, practiced\u00a0\nsince about 7,000 BC, especially in southern\u00a0\u00a0 China; the production of silk; and the processing\u00a0\nof bronze, which began around 3,000 BC. The\u00a0\u00a0 introduction of bronze work was accompanied by\u00a0\nnew technologies that decisively changed art,\u00a0\u00a0 agriculture and, not least, warfare.\nBut before we dive right into the depths\u00a0\u00a0 of Chinese history, take a moment and relax:\u00a0\nlook, cold turkey may be great on sandwiches,\u00a0\u00a0 but there\u2019s a better way to break your bad habits.\u00a0\nAnd right now I\u2019m not talking about some long\u00a0\u00a0 forgotten ritual from ancient China, I\u2019m talking\u00a0\nabout the sponsor of this video F\u00dcM. They look\u00a0\u00a0 at the problem in a different way\u2026Not everything\u00a0\nin a bad habit is wrong, so instead of a drastic,\u00a0\u00a0 uncomfortable change why not just remove the\u00a0\n\"bad\" from your habit? F\u00dcM in an innovative,\u00a0\u00a0 award-winning flavored air device that does\u00a0\njust that. Instead of electronics, F\u00dcM is\u00a0\u00a0 completely natural. Instead of vapor, F\u00dcM uses\u00a0\nflavored air. AND instead of harmful chemicals,\u00a0\u00a0 F\u00dcM uses all-natural flavors. You get it\u2026 Instead\u00a0\nof bad, F\u00dcM is good. F\u00dcM is a habit you\u2019re free to\u00a0\u00a0 enjoy and makes replacing your bad habit easy. It\u00a0\nfills the void in a natural, guilt-free way. Y